tive library. JNA typically loads user32, but I need to ensure it finds a minimal libuser32.so with the necessary symbols. There's a lot to consider, like initializing Ddeml and how JNA resolves symbols at load time. I might create a symlink to libc, but I'm cautious about portability and runtime implications.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering JNA Library Paths**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using the JNA system property jna.library.path to point to a generated dummy library. However, generating a native library directly in Java tests seems impossible without a compiler, which isn't suitable for my needs. Another option could be to set something like com.sun.jna.Native.POINTER_SIZE, but that may not help. Ultimately, I need to ensure that Ddeml.<clinit> succeeds for everything to work properly, which is a key point in my approach.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_yYAtYbzr66W94KM2bd2jdaRs|fc_0cca6e5ebb9c88ce016a10a7b6618c81a086b6617c8a8be654", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find /tmp/metadata-forge-gradle ~/.gradle ~/.m2 -path '*net.java.dev.jna/jna/5.3.1*' -type f -name 'jna-5.3.1.jar' 2>/dev/null | head -5"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 5118, "output": 1216, "cacheRead": 30720, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 37054, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779476385251, "responseId": "resp_0cca6e5ebb9c88ce016a10a7a22c6881a0ac03f162239b36e1"}}
